<TEXT>
the jury in leona helmsleys tax evasion trial 
ended a third day of deliberations without a verdict monday after 
rehearing testimony from liquor salesmen who said they gave 
kickbacks to the hotel magnate 
the jurors in manhattans federal court deliberated 8 hours in 
the third day of discussions they had deliberated about 15 hours 
over the weekend 
mrs helmsley 69 is charged with evading 12 million in 
federal taxes by charging personal expenses including renovations 
at her connecticut mansion to her businesses 
her codefendants former aides turco and joseph licari are 
charged with assisting in the scheme 
mrs helmsley is charged with 41 of the 47 counts in the 
indictment including conspiracy to defraud the internal revenue 
service tax evasion signing false personal returns aiding in the 
filing of false corporate returns mail fraud and extortion 
conspiracy 
the panel on monday asked to rehear testimony from two liquor 
salesmen who testified that they were forced to kick back a 
percentage of their sales to keep accounts at helmsley hotels 
the testimony relates to the most serious charge against mrs 
helmsley conspiracy to commit extortion which carries a 20year 
prison sentence upon conviction 
the jurors also asked to hear the portion of her attorneys 
closing argument which described the payments as rebates and the 
prosecutors rebuttal on that issue 
judge john walker jr however told them they could not hear the 
closing arguments because they are not considered evidence 
the jury has been sequestered since closing arguments began 
wednesday they heard from 44 prosecution witnesses and four defense 
witnesses during the twomonth trial 
</TEXT>
