<TEXT>
ramstein west germany thomas wenzel says a broken watch that 
belonged to his fiance is forever frozen at a most chilling time 
the exact moment she died 
karin schneider was among thousands of people who flocked to the 
ramstein us air base one year ago to watch a spectacular air show 
she was among 70 who died when a flaming jet plunged into the 
horrified crowd 
i have to learn to forget but i cant because of karin says 
wenzel 24 a university student from the nearby village of 
erfenbac i ask myself over and over whether she suffered for a 
long time or whether she died instantly 
only her pocketbook and watch are left the watch stopped at 
the exact second of her death it was 345 in the afternoon 
it was sunday aug 28 1988 an elite team of 10 italian stunt 
flyers were executing a complex move for the thrilled masses below 
two aircraft suddenly collided then a third 
all crashed with one sleek jet bursting into a fireball and 
rocketing downward into the crowd below 
the three pilots were among the dead at least 450 were injured 
since then the ramstein disaster has prompted a national debate 
over air safety 
some critics insist rescue efforts were bungled by lack of 
coordination between west german and us authorities 
others use the tragedy to build their case against lowflying 
aircraft in west germany the bulwark of the us military presence 
in western europe but american and other nato officers point out 
that the italian frecce tricolori team was a stuntflying group that 
had nothing to do with lowlevel flights 
never again and stop lowlevel flights read some of the 
banners during an aug 13 protest march sponsored by a leftist group 
called let us not forget the demonstrators about 1000 of 
them carried 70 crucifixes symbolizing the dead 
later the group watched a mock hearing complete with fivemember 
jury that severely criticized west german and us officials 
involved in planning the air show that attracted more than 300000 
people 
one of those who testified was edna kreutzer who complained 
that officials are refusing to compensate her for the lost wages she 
was expecting from her 23yearold son aloysius one of the 61 west 
germans killed 
he was a miner with a good job and he made a lot of money 
the 52yearold saarland woman said later she works nights bundling 
newspapers to help make ends meet 
the zdf television network says officials have received 1500 
claims for compensation but that so far only half of them have been 
settled it said 81 million has been paid out but that the total 
sum will be several times higher 
wenzel told the associated press his injuries were limited to 
seared lungs and singed hair even though he was standing near karin 
at the time of the crash many other survivors suffered nearly 
incapacitating burns 
in bonn conservative lawmakers are at odds with the leftist 
social democrats over the direction of a special commission that has 
been investigating the crash but the social democrats brush off the 
criticism that it is using the commission in hopes of exploiting 
antimilitary sentiment in next years national elections 
we want to be sure that ramstein never occurs again said 
social democrat defense expert erwin horn 
as part of the observances for the anniversary nato nations are 
grounding all military missions in the normally crowded skies over 
west germany on monday 
the us air force held an anniversary remembrance for the 
victims including the four americans who died on friday at the 
sprawling ramstein base 
west german state lawmakers planned an ecumenical prayer service 
for sunday in ramstein 
and the italian stunt team planned to make its first appearance 
since the disaster performing at an air show in belgium on sunday 
