<TEXT>
the discovery of what appears to be 
active ice volcanoes on neptunes moon triton overshadowed some 
other interesting findings by the voyager 2 spacecraft 
a day on neptune lasts 16 hours and three minutes give or take 
four minutes a day is the time the bulk of a planet takes to spin 
on its axis 
winds up to more than 700 mph blow in neptunes atmosphere 
tiny dust particles vaporized in 100000degree fahrenheit 
microexplosions as they hit voyager when it passed through the 
plane of neptunes rings an onboard sensor recorded the explosions 
which sound like heavy rain falling on a roof the particles were 
about the size of smoke particles too small to hurt voyager 
neptunes south pole and equator while incredibly cold are 
hotter than the planets middle latitudes 
neptunes magnetic poles are tilted 50 degrees away from the 
poles around which the planet rotates a much greater tilt than the 
minimum of 30 degrees scientists initially estimated that means 
neptunes magnetic north pole is closer to its equator than to its 
rotational north pole earths magnetic poles are tilted 12 degrees 
from its true or rotational poles 
</TEXT>
