the skull of a bear has been unearthed on the site 
of the elizabethan rose theater where william shakespeare is 
believed to have acted and near where bearbaiting was first 
recorded in the 1500s 
dr sebastian payne of the historic buildings and monuments 
commission who examined the skull was quoted in the times of 
london today as saying the animal was believed to be a mature adult 
european brown bear 
he said the canine teeth were broken off possibly to make the 
bear less dangerous to humans and dogs and because the teeth were 
subsequently worn smooth the animal must have survived its ordeal 
for some time he said the skull appeared to have come from a ditch 
that contained debris dating from 15871606 when the rose theater 
was flourishing 
bears were brought to britain to undergo the torments of attacks 
by dogs for the entertainment of paying spectators the discovery of 
the skull may indicate the rose was used for entertainment other 
than drama 
the rose site is near the more famous globe theater both stood 
on the south bank of the thames river by southwark bridge 
the foundations of the rose were discovered earlier this year 
during demolition to build an office they are the only relics of an 
elizabethan theater yet found 
