<TEXT>
a general strike called by sinhalese 
radicals brought nearly all businesses and transportation to a halt 
in most of sri lanka on monday 
despite government efforts to keep everything open on the first 
day of the weeklong strike witnesses said almost all shops hotels 
offices and businesses had closed by evening in colombo and most of 
southern and central sri lanka witnesses said those areas make up 
the heartland of sri lankas majority sinhalese community 
you cannot even get a cup of tea today said dharmasena 
attygalle a shipping clerk who walked to work in colombo but found 
his office closed 
the radicals are fighting the sinhalesedominated government 
because they believe it has granted too many concessions to ethnic 
tamil rebels and has not done enough to force a pullout of indian 
peacekeeping troops 
heavily armed troops patrolled colombo in trucks with 
loudspeakers urging shop owners to open their businesses soldiers 
broke locks on some shop doors witnesses said 
however owners forced to open simply closed again when troops 
left witnesses said 
armed troops escorted private and staterun buses but the main 
roads were empty by evening 
the strike was the latest in the series of work stoppages called 
by the peoples liberation front in recent weeks as part of its 
violent 2yearold antigovernment campaign that has claimed at 
least 5000 lives 
the ultranationlist radicals are protesting what they view as 
genocide by the military the radicals say the military armed with 
emergency laws has killed hundreds of front members 
opposition parties and human rights groups also accuse the 
military and progovernment vigilante groups of killing civilians 
suspected to be front sympathizers during a recent crackdown ordered 
by president ranasinghe premadasa the government denies the charge 
the front also protests the presence of indian peacekeeping 
troops in the northeast deployed two years ago to help end an 
ethnic tamil rebellion for an independent nation the radicals say 
the indian presence compromises the countrys independence 
radical posters on buildings monday asked soldiers and policemen 
to resign or face death 
other posters believed to have been created by progovernment 
groups warned sinhalese radicals their families would meet the same 
fate 
an official of the government information department who spoke 
on condition of anonymity said all major newspaper groups have 
indicated they will not publish tuesdays editions the official 
said few staff members arrived for work monday 
the latest report of violence in the radicals campaign came 
sunday when sinhalese militants shot to death a soldiers parents 
brother and sister at their home near colombo military officials 
said 
the front launched its antigovernment campaign soon after the 
first indian troops arrived on june 30 1987 to enforce an 
indiabrokered peace plan to end the tamil insurgency 
the peace plan which promised limited tamil autonomy fell apart 
when the largest tamil rebel group began attacking indian soldiers 
at least 11000 people including about 1000 indian soldiers 
have been killed in the 6yearold rebel war 
a spokesman for the indian embassy said monday that indian troops 
killed nine tamil rebels since sunday in the north and east three 
soldiers also died in the battles the spokesman said speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
the tamils who make up 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million 
people say they suffer discrimination from the sinhalese majority 
sinhalese make up 75 percent of the population 
