<TEXT>
a court ruling against the energy departments 
award of a 1 billion management contract for the nations first 
highlevel nuclear waste dump wont necessarily delay the project a 
senior department official said monday 
us claims court judge reginald gibson ruled last thursday that 
the department could award the contract to no one but trw 
environmental safety systems inc an unsuccessful bidder which sued 
on grounds that the departments means of selecting bechtel systems 
management inc as manager was improper and unfair 
over the short run i cant see that thats a dramatic impact 
on the program said samuel rousso acting director of the 
departments office of civilian radioactive waste management which 
is administering the problemridden project 
he said the department had not yet decided how to respond to 
gibsons ruling including whether to appeal 
the full decision paper has to be analyzed to see what the 
thrust of the judges position is and how we feel about that and 
what we are at liberty to do about that he said in an interview 
in his office at department headquarters 
rousso said preparatory work for studies to determine the 
geologic suitability of the proposed repository site at yucca 
mountain about 100 miles northwest of las vegas nev is not 
affected by gibsons ruling the studies are being held up however 
by nevadas refusal to grant the necessary environmental permits 
nuclear utilities are anxious to see the repository built because 
some are being forced to spend millions of dollars to expand 
temporary waste storage facilities utilities customers pay 400 
million a year into a fund for the permanent dump 
rousso said significant delays in opening the dump by the target 
date of 2003 could result if gibsons ruling which is temporarily 
sealed under court order forces the department to abandon its 
plans to put a single company in charge of much of the project 
he said justice department lawyers were still reviewing the 
ruling and that neither he nor energy secretary james d watkins had 
studied details of the decision 
gibson last week announced only the gist of his ruling saying he 
would give the companies involved until wednesday to review the 
formal document for any proprietary information or trade secrets 
that should be removed before it is made public 
rousso also reiterated his denial of one of trws main charges 
that his involvement in the contract award process was a conflict of 
interest trw asserted that the award was tainted by the fact that 
rousso worked for science applications international corp a 
bechtel subcontractor before joining the energy department 
rousso said he worked for science applications for seven months 
before coming to the department in 1986 the yucca mountain contract 
proposal did not exist then he said adding that he has no 
continuing ties with science applications 
i hold no pension rights no favoritism no job promises no 
thoughts to that regard and i dont see where any conflict of 
interest has been shown he said 
under federal law energy department supervisory employees cannot 
knowingly participating in department projects that involve any 
energy company for which they worked within the past year 
