<TEXT>
the evangelical lutheran church in america 
voted overwhelmingly monday to sell all stock in companies operating 
in south africa by sept 1 1991 despite objections the 
denomination could lose money 
prudence is a christian virtue and im not going to listen to 
pagan lawyers tell me how to be a prudent christian said bishop 
william lazareth of new york city who supported the deadline 
an estimated 85 percent of the 1041 delegates voted for the 
deadline in a showofcards vote at stake was the churchs 16 
billion pension fund of which 849 million is invested in 
companies doing business in south africa 
the meeting is the first since the 1988 merger of the lutheran 
church in america the american lutheran church and the association 
of evangelical lutheran churches 
the divestment move is aimed at pushing south africa to end 
apartheid which establishes a racially segregated society in which 
the countrys 28 million blacks are dominated by 5 million whites 
its a matter of outrage said bishop harold jensen of 
washington dc we cant deal with it simply on a rational 
basis 
several protestant denominations particularly the episcopal 
church the united church of christ the church of the brethren and 
the quakers have had strong divestment policies but none has sold 
all its holdings 
the assembly in the sixth day of an eightday meeting also 
approved a major missions program for the 1990s 
the vote on divestment followed nearly three hours of debate 
among delegates in the 53 millionmember denomination the 
thirdlargest among us protestants 
before the vote investment specialist john kapanke president of 
the denominations board of pensions said a deadline threatened 
financial responsibility 
kapanke said at a news conference later that constraints on 
investments could jeopardize them and increase risks 
he and others said the denomination could be opening itself to a 
lawsuit accusing it of violating its fiduciary responsibility 
we should not fight our social battles with other peoples 
money said the rev elvin bjork of salem ore we could do a 
great deal of damage to the pension fund 
deadline supporters argued that fiduciary meant faithfulness 
to justice as well as to money 
bishop sherman hicks of chicago said all things belong to god 
including money and that the church has do whats right 
regardless of what he called lesser considerations 
a resolutions committee had proposed a measure asking the 
pensions board to work more aggressively to sell off the stock but 
set no deadline however the delegates chose the stiffer 
substitute offered by bishop david olson of minneapolis 
in addition to setting the 1991 deadline the resolution defined 
companies to be divested as those with direct and indirect 
operations in south africa 
