casino owner victoria adams said she had just left the building 
when the mob stormed it and set the fire with molotov cocktails she 
said the mob tried to burn other casinos on the reservation but were 
fended off by armed guards 
state police said the conflict involved upwards of 500 
people the incident lasted about six hours 
while state troopers set up roadblocks to reroute traffic around 
the reservation warriors society members expecting state police to 
intervene set up their own armed checkpoints just inside the 
reservation 
after several tense hours both sides relinquished their 
respective strongholds along the perimeter of the reservation which 
was the site of a 10day standoff between troopers and the warriors 
after a gambling raid july 20 by state and federal authorities 
gambling is illegal in new york and state officials have 
contested the tribes right to operate casinos the mohawks contend 
they are not bound by state or federal gambling laws since they 
consider their reservation a sovereign nation 
progambling mohawks voted this month to permit gambling on the 
reservation but antigambling indians claim the vote was invalid 
state police and tribal leaders reached an agreement this month 
to resume patrols on the reservation but the warriors society has 
said they would allow troopers on their land only with advance 
notice and escorts 
