<TEXT>
 
 
blind mans zoo elektra 10000 maniacs 
 
the beguiling folkrock band from upstate new york 10000 
maniacs are an unlikely success story dont expect them to sound 
happy about it 
teenage pregnancy environmental poisoning rural poverty 
vietnam and central america are all addressed on the dour blind 
mans zoo the strong followup to the maniacs breakthrough lp 
in my tribe 
singer and lyric writer natalie merchant takes somewhat overdone 
political topics and gives them a fresh twist her songs are almost 
like short stories printed on lyric sheets in paragraph form and 
often having only vague connections to the accompanying music 
on the big parade the teenage son of a vietnam war widow 
makes a pilgrimage to the war memorial in washington questioning 
the sense of the conflict that killed his father merchant ends on a 
questioning note abraham had his war too but an honest war or 
so its taught in school 
merchant takes the voice of a soontobe teenage parent on the 
jaunty melody eat for two dream child in my head is a 
nightmare born in a borrowed bed she sings neatly capturing the 
nightmarish aftereffects of one nights mistake 
the delicate trouble me about wanting to take some of the 
burden off the shoulders of a sick friend is particularly 
entrancing 
the four men behind merchant all take turns writing music mostly 
folkrock with occasional harder touches despite the continued 
succession of downbeat topics the record meets the challenge set by 
in my tribe 
that said warning signs abound the record hews so closely to 
the sound of its predecessor that it can almost be called in my 
tribe part 2 10000 maniacs songs tend to be harmonically 
similar so the lesser compositions veer quickly into boredom that 
doesnt bode well for longevity 
rem had a similar problem of how to build on the success of a 
signature sound they succeeded after a few stumbles a similar 
challenge awaits 10000 maniacs 
by david bauder associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
blaze of glory aampm joe jackson 
 
joe jacksons music has changed in the 10 years since his first 
record 
as part of englands new wave jacksons early songs were 
guitarbased concise and almost hurried they packed a punch but 
the approach had limitations 
jackson soon decided there was no need to rush to make his case 
he became more deliberate and began to vary the instrumentation and 
style of his music 
blaze of glory for example offers the sounds of music halls 
down to london broadway torch ballads sentimental thing 
and eastern europe the instrumental acropolis now and thats 
just on side 1 theres also funk pop ballads and rock n roll 
jackson produced the record and coaxed fine performances from the 
many musicians involved he shares the vocals with three others 
even giving away his prettiest melody sentimental thing to 
singer drew barfield 
tying the package together is jacksons anger the one constant 
since his new wave days several titles here in fact would have 
fit on his 1979 debut album you and me against the world 
rant and rave nineteen forever and evil empire 
in the same vein is the dramatic title cut about an entertainer 
named johnny who dies young 
he went out in a blaze of glory and you and i just fade 
away jackson sings with envy and bitterness the convincing 
performance is also an ironic one it offers evidence that jackson 
rather than fading is a talent still on the rise 
by steven wine associated press writer 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

