japan will have plenty of room for american 
beef if us producers remain competitive in the international 
market the japanese ambassador to the united states said during a 
tour of montana 
by the end of 1991 american beef can come into japan on a 
free competitive basis nobuo matsunaga said as he began a 
threeday tour of montana including several ranches your rivals 
are argentina and australia so you must remain competitive there 
is much room for beef in japan 
opening up japan to us beef exports has helped our ranchers a 
great deal said us sen max baucus dmont chairman of the 
senate international trade subcommittee nationwide ranchers 
incomes increased about 800 million in 1988 largely a result of an 
agreement reached that year with japan to open a market that is 
expected to reach 2 billion annually 
recent cattle price increases also stem from opening the japanese 
market to us exports baucus said us beef exports most going 
to japan increased the value of the average feed steer by 75 in 
1988 he said 
matsunaga was asked friday about the purchase of the selkirk 
ranch near dillon in southwestern montana by the zenchiku meat 
importing company of japan and the purchase of a beef slaughtering 
plant in yakima wash by another japanese exportimport firm 
these are commercial talks between interested parties said 
matsunaga our policy is not to intervene in business talks if 
these investments are successful im sure it will be followed by 
others 
baucus said the japanese beef market was almost completely closed 
to us exports until last year 
although japanese consumers clearly wanted to purchase high 
quality us beef beef was for years the most popular foreign 
purchase for japanese tourists returning to japan us beef 
exports were kept out of japan by a tight quota and other 
barriers said baucus the japanese did agree to ease these 
restrictions somewhat in 1984 but most remained in place until 
1988 
baucus said that in 1988 after seven years of almost continuous 
negotiations the united states and japan signed an agreement that 
obligates japan to phase out its beef quota and most other 
government barriers to beef imports by 1991 
the quota will be replaced by a 75 percent tariff that would be 
reduced over three years although the tariff is high all 
government surcharges and tariffs in 1988 comprised an effective 
tariff rate of about 100 percent 
