<DOCNO> AP890828-0253 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
midway airlines a growing carrier facing a 
possible takeover threat said monday it is strengthening its 
defenses against hostile suitors 
chicagobased midway said it had loosened the trigger on its 
shareholder rights plan commonly called a poison pill by 
lowering to 15 percent from 20 percent the portion of its 
outstanding common stock that an outsider would have to acquire to 
kick the plan into action 
at that point all shareholders except the outsider would be 
entitled to buy additional midway stock at belowmarket prices 
potentially raising the amount the outsider would have to pay to buy 
enough shares to control the company 
midway is strengthening its takeover defenses just three weeks 
after ampcopittsburgh corp a pittsburghbased manufacturing 
company disclosed that it had acquired a 66 percent stake in 
midway and said it might seek control of the airline 
midway said monday in a statement its action was not taken in 
response to any known effort to acquire control of the company but 
was designed to ensure that midway shareholders would receive fair 
and equal treatment in the event of any future proposed takeover 
midway also said the amended shareholder rights plan guards 
against partial tender offers open market accumulations and other 
abusive tactics to gain control of midway airlines without 
negotiations with the board of directors 
ampcopittsburgh spokesman marshall berkman declined to comment 
on the development 
a poison pill alone is not considered a complete takeover shield 
but such plans often become the subjects of legal battles in 
takeover wars which slows down an unwanted suitor 
midway the nations 16thlargest carrier operates from midway 
airport on chicagos southwest side 
in 10 years midways markets have grown from three destination 
cities to 51 the airline recently began firstclass service and has 
ordered 74 new jets from mcdonnelldouglas corp worth about 2 
billion 
</TEXT>
